  "prompt": "Is it generally understood that money laundering is illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, it is generally well understood that money laundering is illegal in virtually all jurisdictions around the world. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legal or \"clean.\" This typically involves three main stages: \n\n1. **Placement**: Introducing illicit funds into the financial system.  \n2. **Layering**: Conducting complex transactions to obscure the origin of the funds.  \n3. **Integration**: Reintroducing the laundered funds into the economy as seemingly legitimate assets.\n\nMoney laundering is prohibited because it enables criminal activities such as drug trafficking, terrorism, fraud, and corruption to thrive. Most countries have stringent laws and regulations in place to combat money laundering, often requiring financial institutions to monitor and report suspicious activities. Penalties for money laundering can include severe fines, imprisonment, and asset forfeiture.\n\nGlobal efforts to combat money laundering are coordinated by entities like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), which sets international standards and promotes effective implementation of anti-money laundering (AML) measures.",
